<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-06T15:04:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-06T15:04:00-05:00" n="913" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d913">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2744.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Chihuahua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-06T13:00:00-07:04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 6, 1912—1 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Orozco elected governor by State congress. No action taken with reference
                            to secession. Remarkable change in the situation within a few hours,
                            undoubtedly attributable to fear of intervention; prospects rather more
                            favorable.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>